<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The key event of the week will be Wednesday's Pounds 2bn auction of stock
yielding 8 1/2 per cent and maturing in 2005.
Both Mr Nigel Richardson of Yamaichi International (Europe) and Mr Simon
Briscoe of SG Warburg Securities expect the auction to go well, since the
stock is likely to become a benchmark issue.
Furthermore, Mr Briscoe thinks the Bank of England will be able to launch a
further tranche of the stock at one of the later auctions this year.
A successful auction would come as a great boost to a market battered by the
recent rise in US Treasury bond yields and some poorish UK inflation
statistics. Ten-year yields have been trading around 9 per cent but Mr
Briscoe thinks gilts could now be due for a rebound.
The monthly meeting between Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank and Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, has been brought forward to today because of
the latter's commitments to the IMF meeting in Madrid later this week. Few
expect a further base rate rise so soon after September 12's half point
increase.
In the absence of much in the way of UK economic statistics, international
markets will have a substantial influence, with traders watching closely for
the outcomes of meetings of the Federal Reserve and the Bundesbank this
week.
</TEXT>
