<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Company News (This Week): Profitability in view after bumpy
ride - Fiat
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
On Thursday, Fiat, Italy's biggest private sector industrial group, will
publish its half-year results, providing the first concrete indications of
how it is working towards the objective of full-year profits outlined by Mr
Gianni Agnelli, group chairman, at the shareholder meeting in June.
Last year, the group revealed a L966bn (Pounds 393.5m) loss for the first
half - which became a record L1,783bn (Pounds 726.2m) loss in the full year
 -and a complex cash-raising plan worth a total of L5,000bn. The group's
shares fell sharply afterwards.
This year's half-year announcement should be less dramatic. Analysts are
more or less in agreement that the group will show a small pre-tax profit
for the first half.
Fiat cars - which include the Alfa Romeo and Lancia brands - have managed to
increase their market share in Italy, with the help of a competitive
exchange rate which has deterred buyers of rival foreign marques, in
particular Japanese.
Exports should also show strong growth, for the same reasons, with the Fiat
Punto, launched last year, leading the recovery.
The prospect of good results is already in the Fiat share price, according
to analysts, and investors may be more concerned next week by the Italian
government's efforts to push through a 1995 budget.
</TEXT>
