<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Lufthansa to cut debt by DM3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lufthansa, the German national airline, plans to reduce the group's
long-term net debt by nearly DM3bn (Pounds 1.2bn) by 1997 as part of its
overall restructuring and financial recovery.
The reduction in net debt will lead to annual interest payment savings of
around DM200m a year by 1997 in addition to the DM500m-DM700m in annual
savings the company is seeking to achieve from its restructuring and
cost-cutting strategy, according to Mr Klaus Schlede, Lufthansa's deputy
chairman and chief financial officer.
Mr Schlede said Lufthansa would use all the proceeds of the DM1.2bn it is
raising from its current rights issue to repay ahead of schedule a DM1.2bn
Euroloan maturing in 2000. During a road-show to promote the issue, which is
an integral part of the airline's privatisation programme, Mr Schlede also
disclosed the airline would retire ahead of schedule another DM500m floating
rate bond in the current quarter.
The airline has already repaid DM250m of the floating rate bond in July and
intends to retire the rest next month. 'By the end of this year we will have
reduced our net debt from DM5.9bn to DM4.2bn,' Mr Schlede said. This DM1.7bn
reduction would lead to annual interest payment savings of DM100m by next
year.
In the next two years, two further bond issues will come to maturity
including DM300m next year and DM750m in 1996. 'We will repay these loans
out of cashflow as we see no need for new indebtedness,' he said.
With the repayment of these further Eurobond issues, the group's long-term
debt will be cut to DM3.15bn by the end of 1996, close to its three-year
target of DM3bn. This will lead to the annual DM200m interest payment
savings the group is seeking.
</TEXT>
