<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / This Week: Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If I were Lennox Lewis, I shouldn't mind too much about losing my WBC
heavyweight championship to American Oliver McCall. I should think: I am a
multi-millionaire; I have kept my beauty and my brain intact; I have perhaps
done as well as any man ever did out of this dangerous, destructive sport. I
have simply lost a title, the currency of which is dropping faster than the
pound on Black Wednesday.
Boxing used to impress me more than any other sport. Before a fight I would
go through agonies of vicarious fear, unable to believe that two men were
about to face an unknown, possibly deadly fate.
I would watch the contest in a state of complete tension, willing and
dreading the moment when it would catch fire. In that moment - the sparking
of fists, the flare of energies, the sudden awareness that victory and
defeat had become absolute - the world blazed into life; then the moment
would pass into something vicious and bloody and I would hate what I was
watching.
However, its fascination was still irresistible. 'I'm going to the fight,' I
would say to myself and I would thrill and shudder at the thought at what
may lay within those words.
For the boxers of course, the sport still wields this huge and terrible
power. The second round punch that caused Lennox Lewis to stagger like a
drunk about the ring for about half a minute did, effectively, take away
from him his future and give it to Oliver McCall. But to the spectator - or
at least to me, to the taxi driver who took me to the fight, and to the man
who sat there next to me half asleep - the punch has lost its power.
It is now clear that when the world title split into four - the WBC, the WBA
the WBO and the IBF - it was destroyed. It is hard for spectators to believe
in the absolutes in victory and defeat when they know they are watching only
one quarter of an absolute. And, without that belief, the dignity and
significance of boxing disappears. All that is left is a pornographic
excitement, a power of dollars reaching higher than Don King's hair and the
print-out of a brain scan. An exposed myth, some people would no doubt say,
and they are probably right.
The symbol - and, to an extent, the architect - of what boxing has become is
Chris Eubank. Adopting what some think of as an ironic stance (so that's
what he's doing when he poses in the ring), he conceals a real lack of
ability with a show of honesty. He hates what he does, he tells us. He knows
that it is vicious and exploitative. He is only in it for the money. Thus he
gets his blows in first, forestalling criticism of yet another lacklustre
performance by telling us that he intended it to be lacklustre, that he is
intelligent enough to do only what is necessary in order to win.
And Chris Eubank is a tremendous draw. Crowds flock to his appalling fights.
By turning himself into a pastiche of the idea of a sporting celebrity, he
has become a sporting celebrity. He, and whoever invented his tremendously
clever persona, has given British boxing new life even as they help to
destroy it. At the Lewis-McCall fight, it even seemed to me that the crowd
had become a pastiche of a boxing crowd. Hitherto, whenever I have walked
into a fight arena the atmosphere has breathed out like that from a dragon;
but it failed to do so yesterday morning. I realised then that the images of
boxing, deprived of their dignity and significance, are tired, tired, tired.
The posse of tough men, in leather overcoats and sunglasses, shuffling round
the fighter as he makes his way into the ring - they looked tired. So did
the shrewd-eyed promoter with a fine spray of blood and sweat upon his
dinner jacket. So did the seen-it-all men with broken noses and Reggie Kray
accents. So did the bejewelled women, watching near-naked gladiators as if
they were models displaying the new collection from Chanel. So did Oliver
McCall, spitting like a sabre-toothed tiger, thrusting his victory at the
crowd with an aggression to which there was no possible response. They are
all tired. It is all burlesque, and not very entertaining burlesque at that.
In the minute after his knock out though, Lennox Lewis no longer seemed part
of the show. He stood in the ring, amid the people who had climbed
frantically through the ropes and were now wondering why they had done so.
And he looked a little surprised but entirely calm. No doubt the punch had
blunted his awareness, but his attitude still seemed remarkable for its
self-possession. Meanwhile, McCall, strapping around himself the WBC belt
that Lewis's posse had brought into the ring, looked like a thief who had
hit someone round the head in order to steal their property. It seemed then
as if boxing now confers the greater dignity upon the man who loses, rather
than the one who wins.
</TEXT>
