<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / This Week: Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the biggest voices in opera tackles one of the most shocking roles in
the repertoire with the release of Jessye Norman's new recording of Richard
Strauss's Salome (Philips). There have been more sensual interpretations,
but few have matched Norman's grandeur, particularly in Salome's final,
blood-curdling address to the head of the Baptist. James Morris provides
solid support as Jochanaan, Seiji Ozawa directs a fluent performance from
the Staatskapelle Dresden.
There are not too many performers from the Woodstock festival who are still
producing fresh material but Carlos Santana, flanked by his brother Jorge
and their nephew Carlos Hermandez, keeps the flag flying with Brothers
(Island). The startling ambition of 'Transmutation/Industrial' soon settles
down into more familiar territory with all three clan members playing some
mean guitar, just like the old days. This latest mutation of Santana support
the album's release with dates in Manchester tonight and at the Labbatts
Apollo in London from September 28-30.
The young Milanese ensemble Il Giardino Armonico, who have helped to pioneer
the use of period instruments in their native country, release a
meticulously-researched version of Vivaldi's The Four Seasons (Teldec), a
performance full of nuance and shading which ranks with the finest.
Art school favourites Robert Fripp and David Sylvian join forces once again
for their third recorded collaboration with Damage (Virgin), a limited
edition (50,000) compact disc of a live performance from their 1993 World
Tour. Production and sound quality are exemplary, but the whole exercise
sounds a little antiseptic.
Massive Attack let all their heavy ammunition off early in Protection (Wild
Bunch). The album's opening and title track, featuring Tracey Thorn on
vocals, is by far the highlight of a set which too quickly settles into a
lazy, directionless groove and ends with a ludicrous live version of 'Light
My Fire'.
Talking of ludicrous, the vogue for opera 'theme' collections reaches new
heights of absurdity with Opera to Die For (Philips), a compilation of
admittedly wonderful arias by characters about to meet their maker. Probably
not one to play too much as the days get shorter.
</TEXT>
