<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Late move to win priority for West Coast line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has launched a belated attempt to obtain priority status for
a flagship rail project from the European Union.
Supporters of the project said the initial failure to seek a priority
listing for the Pounds 500m West Coast mainline on the EU's programme of
trans-European networks could cost it European funding.
It could also make it more difficult to raise private-sector finance.
The Ecu220bn (Pounds 170bn) plan for a pan-European network of transport
links was launched last December by the European Commission. Its list of
schemes for priority treatment includes high-speed rail links in France,
Germany and Spain and motorways in Spain and Greece.
Local authorities and business groups along the 550-mile West Coast route
between London and Glasgow are furious about the government's failure to act
sooner and are campaigning vigorously for the project to be accorded
priority status.
Britain will try to persuade European Commission officials to add the
project to the priority list at a meeting planned for October 17. But there
are already 11 schemes on the list and other member states are also expected
to propose additions. Schemes agreed in October will be put to the EU summit
in Essen, Germany, in December.
Mr David Cole, economic director of Cumbria County Council, said: 'There is
a lot of campaigning to do to get it on the list because Spain, Portugal and
Italy also have projects they want included. The British government has not
been pushing vigorously enough.'
Private-sector and local authority backers of the Pounds 500m plan to
modernise the West Coast route are divided over the government's reasons for
failing to put the scheme forward earlier when it first had the chance.
Some said British officials might have been sticking too closely to the
formal eligibility guidelines. Others suggested it reflected the low
priority which the government gave to rail compared with road.
The West Coast rail project is intended to modernise the 30-year-old track
and signalling on the route.
A feasibility study is being carried out by Railtrack and WCML Development,
a private-sector consortium. A construction consortium will be selected by
competitive tender to start work next year.
Mr Tony Bradley, business policy manager at the Birmingham Chamber of
Commerce, said: 'It could have been put on the list earlier. We have been
lobbying for the project for the past three years and the list of
trans-European network schemes was only agreed in June.'
Priority status for the West Coast line would mean the project was eligible
for help with feasibility studies and other EU funding.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
