<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / BR shuts down Continental freight service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Rail has closed a subsidiary set up to provide a container service
to continental Europe because it failed to find a buyer in the private
sector.
Haulmark European Transport was established two years ago to provide a
door-to-door service between European destinations. Containers were shipped
by road to a rail terminal or port and then con-tinued their journey by
ferry or through the Channel tunnel.
The company was put up for sale in March but failed to attract an acceptable
bid, either from outside or from its own management.
Industry sources said this was an indication of tough competition in the
transport sector, particularly in the growing field of road-rail transport.
Railfreight Distribution (RfD), the BR subsidiary which runs services to the
Continent, was unable to keep Haulmark going because there would have been a
conflict of interest between its own 'wholesale' activities, running full
trainloads, and Haulmark's operation, selling space on indi-vidual wagons,
the company said.
RfD denied that Haulmark had failed financially although freight industry
sources said the company was understood not to be making money. When it was
put up for sale earlier this year it had turnover of Pounds 12m and employed
19 people at its offices in Woking, Surrey.
Staff numbers have since fallen to 11 and they will be found alternative
employment in RfD.
</TEXT>
