<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Road users fearful over report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Road users' organisations are fearful that a Royal Commission report on
transport issues expected in October will come down heavily in favour of
increased curbs on car use and road journeys.
They are concerned that the weight given to the report will increase
pressure on the government to limit roadbuilding and to increase the cost of
journeys.
The report is seen as giving a seal of approval to ideas expressed by the
traditional critics of government transport policy.
The British Road Federation said: 'The report will have a lot of status but
we fear it will not contain a lot of sense. The commission must understand
that roads and road transport are essential to our economy and to people's
quality of life.'
The Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution has been reviewing transport
policy for the past 18 months. Its report is expected to contain more than
100 recommendations, including shifting the balance of spending towards
public transport, raising fuel taxes and charging cars to enter congested
city centres.
The Automobile Association hopes the report will not be unfair to the
motorist. It said: 'The car is necessary for people's freedom and mobility.'
Environmental groups said they would welcome a report which called for a
reduction in car use.
The Council for the Protection of Rural England said: 'We anticipate the
report will be reasonably strong. In our evidence to the commission we
called for a proper, integrated transport policy.'
Friends of the Earth said: 'The problem is getting the government to do
something. We don't want a temporary alleviation of the problem. We want a
sea change in government thinking.'
</TEXT>
