<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Pay deals near 4% expected next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Average pay settlements next year are likely to rise to between 3 per cent
and 4 per cent, independent pay analyst Incomes Data Services says in its
annual review, David Goodhart writes.
Stronger economic growth is likely to bring with it much higher levels of
staff turnover, deferred from the recession, and the re-emergence of skill
shortages.
The review also says that pay settlements are likely to continue becoming
more complex and differentiated with the spread of profit-related pay,
all-merit reviews and additional performance awards, making it increasingly
difficult to assess how much a settlement is worth.
In the public sector, the government's pay bill freeze has created an
informal norm of pay rises at or around the rate of inflation. But the
report warns that it may be more difficult to achieve such outcomes in the
second year of the pay-bill freeze.
The report says: 'Labour markets are tightening in the south-east at a much
faster rate than in most of the rest of the country'. In areas such as
Cambridge, Bury St Edmunds, Crawley, Newbury and Winchester unemployment
rates are down to or below 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
