<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Universities want watchdog for standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
University vice-chancellors are calling for a national body to ensure that
standards of teaching and learning are maintained.
A discussion document prepared for this week's annual conference of the
Committee of Vice-Chancellors and Principals says that 'evidence that staff
may be adjusting degree standards to what students can achieve in three
years during which much of their time is in part-time paid work,' suggests
that UK universities have 'already started on the downward slope'.
It adds that the current system, which funds research and teaching
separately, 'unless radically altered, will lead to a gross deterioration in
the quality of the work of universities'.
The report follows criticism of degree classification standards by the
Higher Education Quality Council, the universities' self-regulating body. It
found that standards varied between universities and between faculties.
Its findings demonstrated little consistency and much variation in the
methods used across universities for classifying degrees.
They also showed that universities 'overwhelmingly relied upon individual
departments to draw up assessment and classification schemes without
developing or adopting common marking bands across faculties'.
The quality council raised 'serious concerns' about the adequacy of library
services due 'in the main to the great increases in student numbers'.
Student numbers have doubled as a proportion of the 18-year-old population
in the last five years. In spite of this expansion the proportion of
students gaining first-class honours has increased by 50 per cent.
In a report prepared by Professor Lewis Elton, of the University of Surrey,
vice-chancellors say the creation of a national teaching and learning board
is 'essential'.
Professor Elton says: 'The alternative is that in 20 years our universities
will resemble the worst of what we see, in say, Germany today - vastly
overcrowded lecture halls, no individual attention until a student's third
or fourth year, horrendous drop-out rates, a constant lengthening of course
completion, and a discouraged and despondent staff.'
Management of Teaching and Learning. CVCP 29, Tavistock Square, London WC1H
9EZ. Pounds 5.
Learning from Audit. HEQC, 344-354 Gray's Inn Road, London WC1X 8BT.
</TEXT>
