<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Yeltsin and Major review peacekeeping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIMITRY VOLKOV and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major and President Boris Yeltsin of Russia yesterday reviewed a
range of peace-keeping operations, with emphasis on Bosnia.
Russia has aligned with the UK and other European countries in trying to
dissuade the US from seeking to lift the UN arms embargo and increase the
flow of arms to the Bosnian Moslems.
They also discussed next month's state visit by the Queen to Russia.
On the final day of his visit Mr Yeltsin described it as a weekend of
'useful and enjoyable' talks at Chequers, the prime minister's country
retreat.
Mr Douglas Hurd, Britain's foreign secretary, held more detailed but equally
informal talks with Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, who
will accompany the president on his visit to the UN today.
The UN visit will be followed by a two-day summit in Washington with
President Bill Clinton.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, will meet Mr Alexander
Shokin, the Russian deputy prime minister in charge of international
economic affairs, in London today.
They will discuss prospects for trade and investment in the oil industry and
other areas.
Mr Major, speaking at Brize Norton military airport before Mr Yeltsin's
departure yesterday, praised the 'restraint and courage' shown by the
Russian leadership in recent months.
Mr Yeltsin replied that Russian peace-keeping efforts, often regarded with
suspicion in the west, were aimed at 'extinguishing fires and inter-ethnic
strife.'
Mr Yeltsin said that he was 'somewhat surprised' that western countries had
not come forward to participate in peace-keeping operations in areas such as
Moldova, Ossetia or Nagorno Karabakh, where Russia was mediating between
Armenia and Azerbaijan.
Bosnia and Russian peacekeeping operations in the former soviet states of
the Commonwealth of Independent States are expected to loom large in this
week's summit meeting with President Clinton.
But both sides will lay stress on ways of reducing trade barriers and
encouraging private investment, especially in areas of weakness, such as
telecommunications, agriculture and energy.
President Yeltsin will stress that Russian foreign policy is guided by
national interest, not ideology, when he makes his maiden speech at the UN
today.
</TEXT>
