<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Rabin and Arafat in accord on poll talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HOROVITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel's Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Palestine Liberation Organisation
chairman Yassir Arafat held a remarkably good natured meeting yesterday,
agreeing that negotiators from each side would meet in Cairo next week to
plan the details of Palestinian elections.
In marked contrast to the tense, ill-natured atmosphere that has
characterised previous talks between them, Mr Rabin and Mr Arafat emerged
from their meeting at the Erez crossing point between Israel and Gaza
smiling and conversing easily with each other, and then held a joint press
conference in which they both played down the differences that are delaying
implementation of the next stages of the Palestinian autonomy accord.
The main conflict is over proposals for elections throughout the occupied
territories, with Israel insisting that only a cabinet-style administrative
body be voted into office to run the Palestinian self rule areas, and the
PLO demanding that a legislative parliament be elected, with about 100
members.
Mr Arafat says he wants to hold the vote on November 1. Mr Rabin says so
early a date is unrealistic.
Negotiators will try to resolve the issue when they meet in Cairo next week.
Separate teams of negotiators, the two men agreed yesterday, will also meet
in Cairo to discuss various security issues.
The key to the unusually pleasant atmosphere at yesterday's meeting probably
lies in Mr Arafat's ready agreement 'to take all measures' to prevent
attacks on Israeli targets by Palestinian extremists opposed to the autonomy
process.
Israel's Central Bank yesterday raised interest rates by 1.5 percentage
points to 15.5 per cent in a renewed effort to curb inflation, writes David
Horovitz.
The governor of the Bank of Israel, Professor Jacob Frenkel, said the sharp
rise was designed to rein in a boom in personal consumption, which is
driving up imports and contributing to a worsening balance of payments
deficit.
Combined with a package of anti-inflationary measures agreed by the cabinet
this month, Prof Frenkel said the rise should help the government meet its
8-11 per cent target for inflation in 1995. Inflation for 1994 is currently
running at 14.5 per cent, double the government's original target.
</TEXT>
