FT  26 SEP 94 / Chirac offer to Balladur
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jacques Chirac, leader of France's ruling RPR Gaullist party, has invited
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur to run as number two on his presidential
ticket next year, in an attempt to avoid fratricide between the two
Gaullists. With no vice-presidential slot in France, Mr Balladur would be
designated as prime minister again if Mr Chirac won the presidency. Mr
Chirac said at the weekend that the idea of such a Chirac-Balladur ticket
had been 'imagined some time ago' and would still 'not necessarily be the
worst solution'. But Mr Balladur appears to have no intention of playing
second fiddle to his party leader. According to an IFOP poll in yesterday's
Journal du Dimanche, Mr Balladur's popularity has dropped sharply, with 52
per cent of French declaring themselves satisfied with his government,
compared with 63 per cent in August. But even 52 per cent is a high rating
for a French prime minister, and Mr Balladur continues to do much better
than Mr Chirac in surveys.
