<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 94 / Union optimistic over rail deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Both sides in the rail dispute were last night edging closer to a deal that
could bring an end to nearly three months of disruption on the network.
After more than 40 hours of talks over five days at the conciliation service
Acas, RMT transport union officials believe a package of measures linking
higher pay to improved efficiency is close to completion. Negotiations are
expected to continue at Acas today.
Last night, union officials said the talks were unlikely to produce an
immediate settlement that could be approved by both the union and Railtrack,
the state-owned company responsible for maintaining the network's
infrastructure.
They said it was more likely the RMT would acknowledge publicly that the
best deal achievable in the circumstances had been negotiated and there was
no possibility of further improvement.
Any deal would have to be put to the union's executive before going to
ballot. The 4,600 signal workers who have staged 19 days of strikes would
have the final say on whether to accept any proposed pay and efficiency
package.
The union executive could decide whether to recommend acceptance or
rejection of the offer but it could not exercise any power of veto. The RMT
could hold a ballot this week if a settlement is reached soon.
Union officials said the RMT would be likely to give some ground to secure a
deal, although it would not give in to all management demands. 'It will be a
typical compromise after a long dispute,' one senior RMT member said.
</TEXT>
