<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 94 / International Company News: Borden signs merger agreement
with KKR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Borden, the beleaguered US food group, formally gave up its independence
yesterday by signing a definitive merger agreement with buy-out specialists
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts (KKR).
KKR's Dollars 2bn bid for Borden, announced two weeks ago, had been
criticised by some shareholders as inadequate.
Mr Frank Tasco, Borden chairman, said 'while the restructuring plan Borden
has pursued since January was progressing, it is clear that Borden requires
substantial further restructuring which would significantly increase the
risks and financial burdens on the company'.
An alternative takeover plan for Borden had been put forward by the investor
Mr Paul Kazarian. The plan involved cash, whereas KKR will pay for Borden
with shares in the food and tobacco group RJR Nabisco. A Borden spokesman
said yesterday Mr Kazarian was free to pursue his offer. Mr Kazarian, whose
ability to raise the money has been doubted in some quarters, was
unavailable for comment.
Mr Tasco said: 'We concluded the benefits of this transaction with KKR -
providing an immediate premium and the opportunity to participate in the
future of RJR Nabisco - represent the clear, best outcome for Borden
shareholders.'
KKR expects to gain control of Borden by the year-end.
