<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 94 / White House press chief keeps her job: Clinton overrules
plan to replace Dee Dee Myers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton has overruled his chief of staff's recommendation to
replace Ms Dee Dee Myers as White House press secretary. A personal appeal
from Ms Myers to the president on Thursday evening appears to have been
instrumental in his decision.
Mr Leon Panetta, the chief of staff, announced an extensive reshuffling of
duties in the White House yesterday afternoon, designed, he said, 'to
establish clear lines of authority'. He added that 'good judgment' had not
always been exercised in the past, a reference to a number of embarrassing
controversies ranging from the travel office to Whitewater-related matters.
Two of Mr Clinton's closest aides, both previously with virtually unimpeded
access to the Oval Office, are given more specified duties. Mr George
Stephanopoulos is to be executive assistant for policy in Mr Panetta's
office, while Mr Bruce Lindsey moves to become a deputy White House legal
counsel. Mr Harold Ickes also gains more power as deputy chief of staff for
policy and political affairs.
But the immediate impact of his changes was diluted by the resolution of Ms
Myers's status. Although Mr Panetta said it was 'not true' he wanted someone
else as press secretary, there seems little doubt that Mr Clinton did
overrule the former congressman and budget director.
His plan, widely circulated in the capital on Thursday, would have had Ms
Myers replaced as press secretary by Mr Mike McCurry, currently the state
department's chief spokesman. She would have been given unspecified broader
responsibilities in the White House communications network.
This prompted Ms Myers to appeal directly to Mr Clinton in what was
described as an 'emotional' session in which she may have threatened to
resign. Mr Clinton, not unaccustomed to making up his mind at the last
minute, decided not only to retain her as press secretary but to give her
greater access to senior policy-makers, including himself.
Ms Myers is the first female press secretary and one of the most visible
women on the team. Her departure under protest would not have looked good,
especially since Mr Panetta's reshuffle also involved two other senior
female staff members. Ms Joan Baggett remains political director but must
now report to Mr Ickes, while Ms Ricki Seidman, in charge of presidential
scheduling, is leaving the government.
</TEXT>
