<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 94 / Ex-Yugoslavia sanctions eased: UN Security Council rewards
Milosevic and puts curbs on Bosnian Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   UNITED NATIONS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The United Nations Security Council early this morning eased sanctions
against the rump Yugoslav state to reward Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic for cutting off supplies to Bosnian Serbs and accepting
international monitors on his border, Reuter reports from the UN.
The vote was 11 in favour, two against and two abstentions. Voting against
were Pakistan and Djibouti. Abstaining were Nigeria and Rwanda. The
resolution was sponsored by the US, Russia, Britain, France, Germany and
Spain.
At the same time the council imposed new travel and economic curbs on the
Bosnian Serbs, with China abstaining because of its general opposition to
sanctions. A third resolution, adopted by a 15-0 vote, condemns ethnic
cleansing in Banja Luka and elsewhere and demands access for UN personnel to
these areas.
The controversial resolution on easing the embargo against the Yugoslav
states of Serbia and Montenegro suspends for 100 days bans on passenger
flights to Belgrade and cultural and sports exchanges. It will also allow
ferry service between the Montengran port of Bar and Bari in Italy.
The measures go into force a day after Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN
secretary general, receives a report from the border monitors that Serbia is
banning all but humanitarian supplies from crossing into Bosnia. The strict
trade embargo against Yugoslavia remains in effect.
Sanctions would return if Mr Boutros Ghali reported that Belgrade was again
shipping proscribed goods across the Bosnian border
The resolution had faced a storm of protests from Islamic member states. In
an official statement they termed it 'nothing less than rewarding the
aggressor, undermining the peace process and sacrificing the principles
enshrined in the UN Charter'.
The US, which joined Russia, Britain, France and Germany in drafting the
proposal, had wanted to delay a vote pending talks that President Bill
Clinton is due to have in New York tomorrow with Bosnian Moslem leaders, but
relented after private consultations with the other members.
Without timely Council action, there were fears that Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic would go back on the agreement.
</TEXT>
