<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 94 / Food &amp; Drink: Fine Pinot Noir at Pounds 4.99 - Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANCIS ROBINSON, NICHOLAS LANDER and JILL JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Not long ago 'affordable Pinot Noir' was rightly regarded as an oxymoron.
Today it is quite possible to find charming, fruity, if relatively
lightweight, Pinots from California for less than Pounds 5.
Oddbins has done more than most to track them down and its Havenscourt Pinot
Noir at Pounds 4.99 has considerably more interest (and less obvious
sweetening) than most.
But now they can also field a fine Pinot Noir at the same price from Chile,
previously terra incognita as a source of delicate Pinot fruit. Hearty
congratulations on Cono Sur Pinot Noir at Pounds 4.99 which shows all of the
jewel-like appeal of simple young Pinot.
The Reserve version is Pounds 5.99 and is also stocked by Tanners, of
Shrewsbury, Shropshire, but at the moment the cheaper wine is the more
charming. (I assumed that Cono Sur was a pun, which only goes to show my
ignorance of Spanish; it means 'southern cone' apparently.)
An indication of how strongly the restaurant industry is growing is provided
by the first issue of Tandoori, a magazine for the 7,500 Indian restaurants
in Great Britain. It is now estimated that there are more Indian restaurants
in the UK than in Bombay or Delhi.
The magazine, founded by Karan Bilimoria, who established the successful
Cobra Indian beer brand in the UK and its editor, Iqbal Wahhab, who set up
East West Communications, to promote the growth of ethnic foods, includes
features on how to market a tandoori restaurant and how Bangladeshi cuisine
may develop in the UK.
The publishers will no doubt be hoping to emulate the success of Patak, a
company which makes Indian spices in Wigan, Lancashire and was named by
Marketing magazine as the fastest growing brand in the UK last year with a
92 per cent growth in retail sales.
Wine lovers should take advantage of the extremely serious wines Italy has
been able to produce from recent vintages. Lea &amp; Sandeman, of Kensington
Church Street, London W8 (071-221 1982) has a special offer of 1990
Supertuscans, of which Il Pergole Torte is a star at Pounds 21.74 while
Oddbins Fine Wine Shops have fallen in love with Rocca Albino's 1991
Piedmont range, including two stunningly seductive Barbarescos, Vigneto
Loreto at Pounds 12.99 and Vigneto Brich Ronchi at Pounds 13.99.
Following the opening of its organic wholefood shop in Yaohan Plaza,
Colindale, north west London, the Japan Centre group has opened another shop
in the capital at 212 Piccadilly.
Foods include: organic shitake mushrooms, tofu, fresh seaweed, sun-dried
fish and squid, green and wheat tea, bonito flakes, noodles, pickled
vegetables, seasonings, dressings and vinegars.
Also available are sea vegetables such as nori (for sushi making) and
instant wakame for miso soup. For those who want to give raw fish a miss,
vegetarian lunch-boxes are freshly made to take away. Also on sale are
Japanese bowls and cookbooks.
The Piccadilly Wholefood and Bookshop is open seven days a week Mon-Sat
10am-7.30pm and Sun 10am-6pm.
</TEXT>
